  "text": "). The oriented edge-vertex incidence matrix S ∈ R |E|×N of G, assigns an arbitrary but fixed direction to each edge, with S k,i = Ai,j and S k,j = − Ai,j if the k-th edge {i, j} is directed from i to j, resulting in the operation (Sx) {i,j} = Ai,j(x(i) − x(j)) at edge {i, j}. Analogously to discrete differential geometry operators and as outlined in prior work [CITATION_1] , L constitutes a graphrealization of a second-order differential operator, while S is linked to a first-order differential operator. Moreover, the matrices are related via L = S T S and have rank N − k for k connected components in G. When the graph is connected with k = 1, we have N (L) = N (S) = z1N , z ∈ R, where N (·) denotes the nullspace.",
